2 SENATE BILL 428
1 Article – Health – General
2 Section 15–141.1
3 Annotated Code of Maryland
4 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
5 BY adding to
6 Article – Insurance
7 Section 15–864
8 Annotated Code of Maryland
9 (2017 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
10 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
11 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
12 Article – Health – General
13 15–141.1.
14 (a) In this section, “Collaborative Care Model” means an evidence–based
15 approach for integrating somatic and behavioral health services in primary care settings
16 that includes:
17 (1) Care coordination and management;
18 (2) Regular, proactive outcome monitoring and treatment for outcome
19 targets using standardized outcome measurement rating scales and electronic tools, such
20 as patient tracking; and
21 (3) Regular systematic psychiatric and substance use disorder caseload
22 reviews and consultation with a psychiatrist, an addiction medicine specialist, or any other
23 behavioral health medicine specialist as allowed under federal regulations governing the
24 model.
25 (b) This section may not be construed to prohibit referrals from a primary care
26 provider to a specialty behavioral health care provider.
27 (c) The Department shall implement and provide reimbursement for services
28 provided in accordance with the Collaborative Care Model statewide in primary care
29 settings that provide health care services to Program recipients.
30 (D) THE DEPARTMENT MAY NOT IMPOSE A COPAYMENT, COINSURANCE, OR
31 DEDUCTIBLE REQUIREMENT FOR SERVICES PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
32 COLLABORATIVE CARE MODEL STATEWIDE IN PRIMARY CARE SETTINGS THAT
33 PROVIDE HEALTH CARE SERVICES TO PROGRAM RECIPIENTS.

SENATE BILL 428 3
1 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
2 as follows:
3 Article – Insurance
4 15–864.
5 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “COLLABORATIVE CARE MODEL” HAS THE MEANING
6 STATED IN § 15–141.1 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE.
7 (B) THIS SECTION APPLIES TO:
8 (1) INSURERS AND NONPROFIT HEALTH SERVICE PLANS THAT
9 PROVIDE COVERAGE FOR SERVICES PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
10 COLLABORATIVE CARE MODEL UNDER INDIVIDUAL, GROUP, OR BLANKET
11 HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, OR SURGICAL BENEFITS TO INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS ON AN
12 EXPENSE–INCURRED BASIS UNDER HEALTH INSURANCE POLICIES OR CONTRACTS
13 THAT ARE ISSUED OR DELIVERED IN THE STATE; AND
14 (2) HEALTH MAINTENANCE ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE
15 COVERAGE FOR SERVICES PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE COLLABORATIVE
16 CARE MODEL UNDER INDIVIDUAL OR GROUP HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, OR SURGICAL
17 BENEFITS TO INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS UNDER CONTRACTS THAT ARE ISSUED OR
18 DELIVERED IN THE STATE.
19 (C) (1) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION,
20 AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION MAY NOT IMPOSE A COPAYMENT,
21 COINSURANCE, OR DEDUCTIBLE REQUIREMENT ON COVERAGE FOR SERVICES
22 PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE COLLABORATIVE CARE MODEL.
23 (2) IF AN INSURED OR ENROLLEE IS COVERED UNDER A
24 HIGH–DEDUCTIBLE HEALTH PLAN, AS DEFINED IN 26 U.S.C. § 223, AN ENTITY
25 SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION MAY SUBJECT SERVICES PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE
26 WITH THE COLLABORATIVE CARE MODEL TO THE DEDUCTIBLE REQUIREMENT OF
27 THE HIGH–DEDUCTIBLE HEALTH PLAN.
28 (C) AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION SHALL PROVIDE COVERAGE FOR
29 SERVICES PROVIDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE COLLABORATIVE CARE MODEL.
30 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That on or before December 1, 2026,
31 the Maryland Health Care Commission shall:
32 (1) conduct a study in accordance with § 15–1501 of the Insurance Article
33 on the impact of eliminating health insurance cost–sharing for services provided under the

4 SENATE BILL 428
1 Collaborative Care Model by insurers, nonprofit health service plans, and health
2 maintenance organizations that provide coverage for services provided in accordance with
3 the Collaborative Care Model under individual, group, or blanket health insurance policies
4 or contracts that are issued or delivered in the State; and
5 (2) report its findings and recommendations, in accordance with § 2–1257
6 of the State Government Article, to the Senate Finance Committee and the House Health
7 Committee.
8 SECTION 3. 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Section 2 of this Act shall
9 apply to all policies, contracts, and health benefit plans issued, delivered, or renewed in the
10 State on or after January 1, 2027.
11 SECTION 4. 5. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Sections 2 and 3 4 of this
12 Act shall take effect January 1, 2027.
13 SECTION 5. 6. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, except as provided in
14 Section 4 5 of this Act, this Act shall take effect July 1, 2026.
